Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.
Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{40%g}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated)
(or use a #garlic press{}).

Put the @couscous{120%g} in a #large bowl{}. Pour in the @boiled water for the couscous{240%ml},
stir in half of the @chicken stock paste{5%g}, then cover tightly with #cling film{}.
Leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} lengthways and discard the core and seeds.

Lay the pepper halves, cut-side down, onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil, then
season with @salt and @ground black pepper{}.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until starting to soften, ~{10-12%minutes}.

While the pepper cooks, heat a drizzle of @oil in a #large frying pan{}.

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and shallot and fry until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any
excess fat.

Season with @salt and @pepper. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling
raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the mince is cooked, stir in the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and
@roasted spice and herb blend{1}. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the remaining @chicken stock paste{5%g} and the @sugar for the sauce{1/2%tsp}
and @water for the sauce{100%ml}. Simmer for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove the roasted pepper halves from your oven. Spoon in the beef mixture and top with
the grated cheese, then return to the oven to bake, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed), then quarter lengthways. Chop into 2cm chunks.

Wipe out the (now empty) #frying pan{} and return to medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the courgette and cook until charred, ~{6-8%minutes} total. Turn only
every couple of mins - this will result in the courgette picking up some nice colour.

When everything's ready, fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}. Stir through the courgette
and @harissa paste{50%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), then share between
your #bowls{}.

Place the stuffed peppers on top of your couscous and serve.

Enjoy!

> This Herby Beef Stuffed Pepper is bursting full of flavours and makes the perfect
> dinner night option. Cook up a fresh start!